definition.value: Catalysis of the transfer of a prenyl group from one compound (donor) to homogentisic acid.
Catalysis of the reaction -  homogentisic acid + farnesyl diphosphate -eq- 2-methyl-6-farnesylplastoquinol.
Catalysis of the reaction -  homogentisic acid + geranylgeranyl diphosphate -eq- 2-methyl-6-geranylgeranylplastoquinol.

Catalysis of the reaction -  homogentisic acid + all-trans-nonaprenyl diphosphate + 3 H+ -eq- 2-methyl-6-solanyl-1,4-benzoquinonone + CO2 + diphosphate. 2-methyl-6-solanyl-1,4-benzoquinonone is also known as 2-methyl-6-solanesylplastoquinol and all-trans-nonaprenyl diphosphate as solanesyl diphosphate.

A protein complex whose composition varies amongst species -  in rice it probably exists in a homo-tetramer to homo-hexamer form and in Gram negative bacteria as a dimer. Functions in the hydrolysis of alpha-(1,6)-D-glucosidic branch linkages. Isoamylases in animals are localized in the extracellular space.

A protein complex whose composition varies amongst species -  in rice it probably exists in a homo-tetramer to homo-hexamer form and in Gram negative bacteria as a dimer. Functions in the hydrolysis of alpha-(1,6)-D-glucosidic branch linkages. Isoamylases in plants are intracellular and probably chloroplast localized.
A region in which centric, heterochromatic portions of one or more chromosomes form a compact structure.
A chromocenter adjacent to the nucleolus.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with double-stranded methylated DNA. Methylation of cytosine or adenine in DNA is an important mechanism for establishing stable heritable epigenetic marks.

label.value: regulation of G2|M transition of mitotic cell cycle

definition.value: Any process that modulates the rate or extent of progression from G2 phase to M phase of the mitotic cell cycle.
Catalysis of the reaction -  S-adenosyl-L-methionine + 3-polyprenyl-4,5-dihydroxybenzoate -eq- S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + 3-polyprenyl-4-hydroxy-5-methoxybenzoate + H+.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with abscisic acid, plant hormones that regulate aspects of plant growth.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a methylated cytosine|unspecified|guanine trinucleotide.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a methylated cytosine|unspecified|unspecified trinucleotide.

Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + 3-oxo-2-(2'-pentenyl)-cyclopentane-1-octanoic acid + coenzyme A -eq- AMP + diphosphate + 3-oxo-2-(2'-pentenyl)-cyclopentane-1-octanoyl-CoA + H+. 3-oxo-2-(2'-pentenyl)-cyclopentane-1-octanoic acid is also known as OPC-8 - 0.
Catalysis of the oxidative cleavage of carotenoids.
Catalysis of the oxidative cleavage of carotenoids at the (9, 10) and|or (9', 10') double bond.

The asymmetric cell division by which a meristemoid mother cells (MMC) give rise to a meristemoid and another cell. The other cell may itself become a MMC or may generate an epidermal cell. Any cell that undergoes this type of division is a MMC.

A small round nuclear body, measuring 0.2-0.8 microns in diameter that is diffusely distributed throughout the nucleoplasm. Several proteins known to be involved in miRNA processing have been localized to these structures. D-bodies are thought to be involved in primary-miRNA processing and|or storage|assembly of miRNA processing complexes.

label.value: cell proliferation in dorsal spinal cord

definition.value: The multiplication or reproduction of cells, resulting in the expansion of the dorsal spinal cord cell population.
The cell cycle process where a cell leaves M phase. M phase is the part of the mitotic cell cycle during which mitosis and cytokinesis take place.
Catalysis of the transmembrane transfer of an ion by a channel that opens in response to a light stimulus.

The multiplication or reproduction of cells, resulting in the expansion of a mesenchymal cell population. A mesenchymal cell is a cell that normally gives rise to other cells that are organized as three-dimensional masses, rather than sheets.

Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of mesenchymal cell proliferation. A mesenchymal cell is a cell that normally gives rise to other cells that are organized as three-dimensional masses, rather than sheets.
Combining with nerve growth factor (NGF), to prevent apoptosis in neurons and promote nerve growth, or to initiate a change in cell activity.
Catalysis of the reaction -  GDP-L-galactose + alpha-D-mannose 1-phosphate -eq- GDP-alpha-D-mannose + alpha-L-galactose-1-phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  GDP-L-galactose + alpha-D-glucose 1-phosphate -eq- alpha-L-galactose-1-phosphate + GDP-alpha-D-glucose.
Catalysis of the reaction -  GDP-L-galactose + myo-inositol 1-phosphate -eq- alpha-L-galactose-1-phosphate + GDP-myoinositol.
Catalysis of the reaction -  GDP + D-glucose 1-phosphate -eq- phosphate + GDP-glucose.
Catalysis of the reaction -  GDP + L-galactose 1-phosphate -eq- phosphate + GDP-galactose.
Any process resulting in the physical partitioning and separation of an epidermal cell, any of the cells making up the epidermis, into daughter cells.

Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the physical partitioning and separation of an epidermal cell into daughter cells. An epidermal cell is any of the cells that make up the epidermis.
Catalysis of the reaction -  acetyl-CoA + histone H3 -eq- CoA + acetyl-histone H3.
Catalysis of the reaction -  acetyl-CoA + histone H4 -eq- CoA + acetyl-histone H4.
Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  Mn2+(in) + H+(out) -eq- Mn2+(out) + H+(in).
Catalysis of the reaction -  S-adenosyl-L-methioninamine + spermidine -eq- S-methyl-5'-thioadenosine + thermospermine + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  UDP-galactose + N-glycan -eq- galactose-beta-1,3-N-glycan + UDP.
Catalysis of the reaction -  UDP-4-keto-6-deoxyglucose -eq- UDP-4-keto-rhamnose.
Catalysis of the reaction -  UDP-4-keto-rhamnose + NADPH -eq- UDP-rhamnose + NADP+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  alpha-L-arabinose 1-phosphate + UTP -eq- UDP-L-arabinose + diphosphate.
A dense aggregation in the cytosol composed of proteins and RNAs that appear when the cell is under stress.

label.value: negative regulation of cell cycle arrest in response to nitrogen starvation

definition.value: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the frequency or rate of cell cycle arrest in response to nitrogen starvation.

label.value: regulation of cell cycle arrest in response to nitrogen starvation

definition.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cell cycle arrest in response to nitrogen starvation.

label.value: positive regulation of cell cycle arrest in response to nitrogen starvation

definition.value: Any process that increases the frequency or rate of cell cycle arrest in response to nitrogen starvation.

Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of recombination during meiosis. Reciprocal meiotic recombination is the cell cycle process in which double strand breaks are formed and repaired through a double Holliday junction intermediate.

Stops, prevents or reduces the activity of a telomerase. Telomerase catalyzes the reaction -  deoxynucleoside triphosphate + DNA(n) -eq- diphosphate + DNA(n+1). Catalyzes extension of the 3'- end of a DNA strand by one deoxynucleotide at a time using an internal RNA template that encodes the telomeric repeat sequence.
Catalysis of the transfer of nitrate from the inside of the cell to the outside of the cell across a membrane.

Any process that modulates a cellular process that is involved in the progression of biochemical and morphological phases and events that occur in a cell during successive cell replication or nuclear replication events.

label.value: regulation of budding cell apical bud growth

definition.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of growth at the tip of a bud, in a cell that reproduces by budding.

label.value: positive regulation of nuclear cell cycle DNA replication

definition.value: Any process that activates or increases the frequency, rate or extent of The DNA-dependent DNA replication that occurs in the nucleus of eukaryotic organisms as part of the cell cycle.
